prsTLE XX.-—Addressed to his book. The poet, pretending that this, the first book of his episties, was anxious to go forth into public, though against his will, proceeds to foretell, like another prophet, the fate that would inevitably accompany this rash design. It is evident, however, from what follows after the 17th verse, that all these gloomy forebodings had no real existence whatever in the poet’s imagination; but that his eye rested on clear and distinct visions of future fame. ’
